textfield.text: Cloning is a java concept through which we can create a duplicate object at run time. In contrast of creating a new object of the same type and setting its property explicitly, cloning creates a bit by bit copy of the object at run time. We can clone a java object if its class is cloneable (implements java.lang.Cloneable). Object class has clone() method that is overridden to create a clone of an object. By default the access modifier of clone() method is protected. If the class to be cloned is expected to be used for cloning outside its package, the modifier must be set to public.

After creation of an object, sometimes extensive time consuming operations are performed on it to bring it into certain state. By cloning this object we can get a copy of this object without going through all the time consuming operations again.
Write a Deep Copy cloneable FruitBasket class having list of Fruits.

For a class to be cloneable it must : Implement Cloneable Interface Override Object class’ clone method Constructor is not called during cloning. Be careful about the access modifier of clone() method while overriding(protected/public). Cloneable is a Marker interface. Deep cloning can also be achieved by serialization. When an object is deserialized we get a clone. This technique is significantly slower as compared to deep cloning achieved by overriding Object class’ clone method.
When an object to be cloned has object reference variables or collections(for example - ArrayList, LinkedList ,HashSet, etc) as member variables, we need a deep cloning to clone it appropriately.

If we clone an object through deep copy, contained object also should be cloned. In the below figure, If a change is made in the department head of dept1, those changes will not be reflected to the dept2.

Default implementation of clone method in Object class copy references of contained objects (We do not have a separate copy of the contained object). In the below figure, If a change is made in the department head of dept1, those changes will also be reflected to the dept2.

Occasionally, you want to use a nested class simply to hide one class inside another, but don’t want the instance of the nested class to be associated to an instance of outer class. You can achieve the goal by declaring it as static nested class. Static nested class is a static member of the enclosing class, so it can access the static methods and variables of the outer class. Static nested class can have both static and not-static member variables. Static nested class is preferred over inner class.

An inner class is associated with an instance of its enclosing class It has direct access to that object's methods and fields. As an inner class is associated with an instance, it cannot define any static members itself.

An inner class is a class that is defined inside another class. Why would you want to do that? There are three reasons: Inner class methods can access the data from the scope in which they are defined—including data that would otherwise be private. Inner classes can be hidden from other classes in the same package. Inner classes are handy when you want to define callbacks without writing a lot of code Depending upon their relation to the surrounding lexical context , classes in java are of two types Top level class-does not appear inside a class or interface, they are normal java classes Nested Class- if a type is not top level, it is nested Member-Directly enclosed by another type declaration Inner (non-static) Static Local classes Anonymous classes Except static nested classes , all other types of inner class can have only non-static variables.

A program can convert an unbuffered stream into a buffered stream There are four buffered stream classes used to wrap unbuffered streams: BufferedInputStream and BufferedOutputStream create buffered byte streams BufferedReader and BufferedWriter create buffered character streams.

Character streams are used for dealing with I/O of character sets. All character stream classes are descended from Reader and Writer. As with byte streams, there are character stream classes that specialize in file I/O: FileReader and FileWriter

Generic methods are methods that introduce their own type parameters. Can be defined in an Ordinary class. Declared without any specific type as argument. Type variable is declared before the return type of the method. Static and non-static generic methods are allowed, as well as generic class constructors.

Static members do not participate in serialization. Order is important in serialization. The order of members during serialization must be the same during deserialization.

When a class is serialized a serial version is created (Using the class name, number of members, their types etc.) and stored besides the state of the object to be serialized. The serial version is concerned during deserialization. If a class is modified after serialization has taken place and an attempt is made to deserialize the previously saved state using the modified class, a version mismatch is identified by JVM and an exception is thrown. Using serialVersionUID , the above problem can be avoided for few compatible operations(like adding a new member in class). Even after using serialVersionUID , there are few operations(for example changing the data type of a member) which can not be avoided and a fresh deployment of the application is required to get the things work appropriately. For the full list of compatible and incompatible operations check the java serialization specification : http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/guide/serialization/spec/version.html#6519

You can implement the Serializable interface and add (notice It is “add” and not “override” or “implement”) methods called writeObject( ) and readObject( ) that will automatically be called when the object is serialized and deserialized, respectively. That is, if you provide these two methods they will be used instead of the default serialization. The methods must have these exact signatures: private void writeObject(ObjectOutputStream stream) throws IOException; private void readObject(ObjectInputStream stream) throws IOException, ClassNotFoundException;

The Externalizable interface extends the Serializable interface and adds two methods, writeExternal( ) and readExternal( ), that are automatically called for your object during serialization and deserialization so that you can perform your special operations.

When a class implements Serializable interface, it is eligible for serialization. This is known default serialization and it takes place automatically. There are two ways of controlling the process of serialization – 1.Using Externalizable interface 2.Direct Serialization(An alternate to Externalizable ) Using the above techniques we can explicitly define the serialization process.

If a class is serializable, all its children automatically become serializable. If a child is serializable but its parent is not, then During child object serialization parent members are not serialized. During deserialization, constructor will be called for the parent class/classes and initialize the parent members.

Create a class “Item” with members as id, name, cost. Create a class “Order” with members as id, description and a list of “Item”. Demonstrate serialization and deserialization using Order object. Note: The state of Item is not required during deserialization.

Serialization is a java technique to save the state of an object. It can be saved on a file system or any other stream. Java’s object serialization allows you to take any object that implements the Serializable interface and turn it into a sequence of bytes that can later be fully restored to regenerate the original object. This is even true across a network, which means that the serialization mechanism automatically compensates for differences in operating systems. Object serialization is byte-oriented, and thus uses the InputStream and OutputStream hierarchies. Serializable is a marker interface. Object serialization was added to the language to support two major features – 1. Java’s remote method invocation (RMI) 2. JavaBeans
“transient” example (using the Item class shown on last slide)

If an specific member of a class is not desired to be saved during serialization, mark it as transient. transient members are assigned their default value during deserialization. Example: int 0 , double 0.0, boolean false , object references null etc. If a class has other member objects, they must either implement Serializable or be marked as transient.

For a class to be serializable it must implement the Serializable interface. To serialize an object, you create some sort of OutputStream object and then wrap it inside an ObjectOutputStream object. Call writeObject( ) and your object is serialized and sent to the OutputStream. To reverse the process, you wrap an InputStream inside an ObjectInputStream and call readObject( ). What comes back is, as usual, a reference to an upcast Object, so you must downcast to set things straight.

There are tools available to create serialVersionUID . Also all the java IDEs like Eclipse, Netbeans etc. support the creation of serialVersionUID . Eclipse supports two ways of creation of serial version ids default serial version id generated serial version id
